defaultAbout the Society for General Microbiology
defaultThe Society for General Microbiology (SGM) is a membership organisation for scientists who work in all areas of microbiology. It is the largest learned microbiological society in Europe wi
defaultth a worldwide membership based in universities, industry, hospitals, research institutes and schools. The SGM publishes key academic journals in microbiology and virology, organises international scientific conferences and provides an international forum 
defaultfor communication among microbiologists and supports their professional development. The Society promotes the understanding of microbiology to a diverse range of stakeholders, including policy-makers, students, teachers, journalists and the wider public, t
defaulthrough a comprehensive framework of communication activities and resources.
default 
defaultFurther information about SGM is provided in Appendix 1.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn early 2013, the Council of the Society for General Microbiology agreed to establish a short-term Working Group to make recommendations to Council to improve the equality of opportunity and diversity of representation in the Society’s membership. The Wor
defaultking Group is chaired by Professor Hilary Lappin-Scott, E
defaultquality and Diversity Champion. 
defaultThe Working Group is currently preparing 
defaultthe SGM Policy on 
defaultEquality and Diversity
default for Council to consider
default.
